subTitle: The Hiroshima and Nagasaki Peace Messengers visit the United Nations in Geneva each year. We join them as they call for nuclear abolition and see the complexities of global politics in a new light.

subTitle: Hourly news updates featuring current affairs, business news, financial updates and global weather forecasts.

title: Karl and Tina : Season's Greetings from a Woodland Village
subTitle: Amid the deep winter snow, a US high school student comes to stay at a house restored by Karl. When spring finally arrives, the villagers celebrate the cherry blossoms and enjoy seasonal dishes.

title: NHK Newsline
subTitle: Hourly news updates featuring current affairs, business news, financial updates and global weather forecasts.

title: Darwin's Amazing Animals
subTitle: Focusing on natural history and exploring the amazing stories of animals in Africa, the Americas and Asia, including Japan. Featuring rarely-seen and unique animals with up-close footage.

title: Time-Lapse Journey
subTitle: A collection of time-lapse photography showcasing the beautiful scenery of Iwate, known as the land of sacred temples.

title: Let's Enjoy Math with Barky the Dog
subTitle: Numbler hides the measuring stick at a shoe shop so that a customer's foot cannot be measured. Barky realises that the measurement can be made by counting how many one-centimetre items are needed.

title: Take Tech
subTitle: Takes a look at the mechanism of the blades of scissors to see how they help cut cleanly and the role of wedges.

title: NHK Newsline
subTitle: Hourly news updates featuring current affairs, business news, financial updates and global weather forecasts.

title: Train Cruise
subTitle: Journeys through the snowy landscapes of Fukui Prefecture in central Japan on the Echizen Railway. Includes traditional meditation at Eiheiji, locally brewed sake, and Echizen crab for dinner.

title: Japanology Plus Mini
subTitle: Japanese paper, known as washi, is attractively textured and extremely durable. In a 5-minute digest, we explore its role in modern society and examine how it represents Japanese aesthetics.

title: NHK Newsline
subTitle: Hourly news updates featuring current affairs, business news, financial updates and global weather forecasts.

title: Spiritual Explorers
subTitle: For 800 years, the Ogasawara family has taught Japanese etiquette through daily actions. We learn how this cultivates self-awareness and understanding of others.

title: Time-Lapse Japan
subTitle: Shugendo, a unique spiritual tradition, dates back 1,300 years. Through time-lapse footage, showing its practitioners and Kumano's sacred forests, long associated with death and rebirth.

title: BOSAI: Science That Can Save Your Life
subTitle: Explore how Japan uses artificial satellites and surface observation to quickly assess flood and earthquake damage, supporting disaster preparedness.

title: Design Museum Japan
subTitle: Long ago, people in Nara preserved ice by building an icehouse on a mountain ridge, showing how architecture can make use of natural characteristics.

title: NHK Newsline
subTitle: Hourly news updates featuring current affairs, business news, financial updates and global weather forecasts.

title: Samurai Castles
subTitle: This castle, 200 km north of Tokyo, was a battleground in Japan's last civil war in the mid-19th century. Modern warfare could not bring it down. We look at the secrets to the its strengths and its lords.

title: Magical Japanese
subTitle: The Japanese language is rich in words and expressions influenced by nature, history and culture. This episode looks at words related to theatre. Explore the unique culture behind them.

title: MATSURI: The Heartbeat of Japan
subTitle: In Saidaiji Eyo, thousands of near-naked men endure icy water and the winter cold as they are purified at a temple. Some of the normal rites are being reintroduced as the pandemic recedes.

title: Protecting Life and Hope
subTitle: Inside Japan's largest pediatric ICU, critically ill children fight for survival while families face life-or-death decisions. This is a six-month record of hope, struggle, and ethical dilemmas.

subTitle: May J presents singer-songwriter Kitamura Fuki, whose work spans various genres of music, and Dreamers Union Choir.

subTitle: Charo sees Candy crying after accidentally jumping into a pool of dirty water. She later reveals that there is one thing she wants to do to return the favour.

subTitle: For hundreds of years, Japanese have used name stamps, known as hanko, to prove their identity. People use stamps in everyday situations, such as receiving a parcel, and in formal contexts, such as business transactions.

title: A Cat's-Eye View of Japan
subTitle: A cat takes a nap among the fragrant flowers at a farm that grows sweet pea flowers, another cat takes a nap at an archery range, and meet more local cats as residents celebrate a unique tradition.

title: Cycle Around Japan
subTitle: While beautiful Aomori can be harsh due to its northern climate, a visiting cyclist enjoys the warmest of welcomes in communities that historically had to cooperate closely in everything in order to survive.

subTitle: I likes to make dolls, but he is afraid that others will find out about his hobby.

subTitle: Charleston, a historic East Coast port city founded in 1670, charms visitors with cobblestone streets, horse-drawn carriages, and rich history. It's loved by both international and US travellers.
